🧠 INTUITION (CORE IDEA)
What happens in one transfer?
Take x from one bank → only y reaches another bank

👉 Loss per transfer:

x - y  (bank profit)
💡 Key Thought

From a bank with a[i]:

👉 How many times can we transfer?

k[i] = a[i] / x

Each time gives:

+ y to some bank
🔥 So each bank contributes:
k[i] transfers → contributes k[i] * y money
🧠 GLOBAL THINKING (IMPORTANT)

We want:

maximize money in ONE bank

So think:

👉 Choose one bank as target

👉 All other banks send money to it

⚡ What can each bank give?

Each bank i:

k[i] = a[i] / x transfers

Total transfers from all banks:

total = sum(k[i])
🎯 If bank i is target
It already has:
a[i]
It cannot send its own money to itself
👉 so ignore its own transfers k[i]
From others it gets:
(total - k[i]) * y
💥 Final formula
cur = a[i] + y * (total - k[i])

Take max over all i

🧠 Why this works (IMPORTANT)

👉 Order of transfers doesn’t matter
👉 Only count of transfers matters

👉 Always optimal to:

Use all possible transfers
Send everything to ONE bank
⚠️ Important Observations
❌ You cannot partially transfer
Must send exactly x
❌ Remaining < x is useless
✅ Only full transfers matter:
a[i] / x
⚡ HOW TO THINK IN CONTEST

When you see:

transfer with loss
maximize final value

👉 Think:

“Count how many full transfers each source can do”

💻 CLEAN CODE
#include <bits/stdc++.h>
using namespace std;

#define ll long long
#define fast_io ios::sync_with_stdio(false); cin.tie(nullptr);

void solve() {
    ll n, x, y;
    cin >> n >> x >> y;

    vector<ll> a(n);
    ll total = 0;

    // count total possible transfers
    for(int i = 0; i < n; i++) {
        cin >> a[i];
        total += a[i] / x;
    }

    ll ans = 0;

    for(int i = 0; i < n; i++) {
        ll k = a[i] / x;

        // current bank as target
        ll cur = a[i] + y * (total - k);

        ans = max(ans, cur);
    }

    cout << ans << '\n';
}

int main() {
    fast_io;
    int t;
    cin >> t;
    while(t--) solve();
}
🧠 FINAL MEMORY BLOCK

👉 For each bank:

k[i] = a[i] / x

👉 Total transfers:

total = sum(k[i])

👉 Answer:

max(a[i] + y * (total - k[i]))
💥 ONE LINE SUMMARY

“Each bank gives ⌊a[i]/x⌋ transfers → send all to one bank → maximize result.”

🚀 Pattern Recognition (VERY IMPORTANT FOR YOU)

This pattern appears when:

fixed chunk transfer (x)
gain per transfer (y)
maximize one entity

👉 Always think:

count contributions → aggregate → choose best receiver
